You now know option() (BOOL) ‚Äî the next step is STRING options in CMake.

I‚Äôll explain what it is, why it exists, and how YOU should use it (conceptually, not dumping code).

üîë What is a STRING option in CMake?

A STRING option lets the user choose one value from many possibilities,
instead of just ON / OFF.

Think of it as:

mode selection

backend selection

algorithm selection

platform selection

üß† Compare BOOL vs STRING (very important)
Type	User can choose
option()	ON / OFF
STRING	Any text value

Examples:

DEBUG, RELEASE

FAST, SAFE

OPENSSL, MBEDTLS

TCP, UDP

üîç When should you use STRING instead of option()?

Ask yourself:

‚ùì Are there more than 2 valid choices?

If YES ‚Üí use STRING

If NO ‚Üí use option()

üß± How STRING variables are defined (conceptually)

In the parent CMakeLists.txt, you:

Create a variable

Put it in the CACHE

Give it a default value

Describe allowed values (for humans)

This makes it configurable via -D.

üß™ How user passes a STRING value

From command line:

cmake -DMODE=FAST ..


or

cmake -DALGORITHM=SAFE ..

üß† Important difference from option()

option() automatically creates a BOOL cache variable

STRING must be explicitly cached

STRING values are not validated automatically

So:

User can type anything ‚Äî YOU must handle it



